1. WHAT THIS STEP DOES
--------------------------------------------------

  Step 5 identifies the precise yield spread values where
  deterministic (average-yield) planning starts to perform
  poorly enough that a practitioner should consider switching
  to stochastic planning.

  Method: 150 experiments (50 spread levels × 3 experiments)
  with 5 failure criteria applied to each, using linear
  interpolation for sub-grid-point precision.


2. THRESHOLD RESULTS — EXPERIMENT A (FE UNCERTAINTY ONLY)
--------------------------------------------------
  This is the most important experiment because FE uncertainty
  is the primary driver of planning approach differences.

  %VSS > 2%:
    Triggered at FE spread = 0.3556
    Between spread 0.3500 (value=1.9615) and 0.3600 (value=2.0307)
    Degradation rate to end of range: 7.22 per unit spread

  %VSS > 1.5%:
    Triggered at FE spread = 0.2021
    Between spread 0.2000 (value=1.4963) and 0.2100 (value=1.5137)
    Degradation rate to end of range: 5.18 per unit spread

  Service gap > 1 unit:
    Triggered at FE spread = 0.3583
    Between spread 0.3500 (value=0.7721) and 0.3600 (value=1.0454)
    Degradation rate to end of range: 28.57 per unit spread

  Service gap > 3 units:
    Triggered at FE spread = 0.4298
    Between spread 0.4200 (value=2.7196) and 0.4300 (value=3.0045)
    Degradation rate to end of range: 29.17 per unit spread

  VSS > $150:
    Triggered at FE spread = 0.4057
    Between spread 0.4000 (value=147.4176) and 0.4100 (value=151.9571)
    Degradation rate to end of range: 466.51 per unit spread


3. THRESHOLD RESULTS — EXPERIMENT B (BE UNCERTAINTY ONLY)
--------------------------------------------------
  BE uncertainty should NOT trigger failure criteria (or trigger
  them only at the baseline level), confirming the no-recourse
  finding from Steps 3-4.

  %VSS > 2%: NOT triggered
  %VSS > 1.5%: Triggered at spread = 0.0100
  Service gap > 1 unit: NOT triggered
  Service gap > 3 units: NOT triggered
  VSS > $150: NOT triggered

  Note: Any triggers here are from the baseline FE spread (0.15),
  not from BE uncertainty changes.


4. THRESHOLD RESULTS — EXPERIMENT C (BOTH TOGETHER)
--------------------------------------------------
  %VSS > 2%: Triggered at spread = 0.3413
  %VSS > 1.5%: Triggered at spread = 0.0100
  Service gap > 1 unit: Triggered at spread = 0.3632
  Service gap > 3 units: NOT triggered
  VSS > $150: Triggered at spread = 0.4065


5. THE FAILURE ZONE — KEY FINDING
--------------------------------------------------

  For FE uncertainty (Experiment A):
    Earliest warning:   spread = 0.2021  (%VSS > 1.5%)
    Latest critical:    spread = 0.4298  (Service gap > 3 units)

  The failure zone for FE uncertainty spans approximately:
    Warning zone:       spread ≈ 0.20 to 0.43
    Critical zone:      spread > 0.43

  In yield terms (FE mean = 0.875):
    Warning when FE yields range wider than [0.774, 0.976]
    Critical when FE yields range wider than [0.660, 1.000]


